concertlist.info: This was only the second time Pearl Jam played "Rain" in its entirety, although it was also briefly teased during the legendary stagedive-performance at Pinkpop in 1992. "Marker in the Sand" was played for the first time since September 2011, and for the first time in Europe since July 2007. "All or None" was played only for the second time since August 2007, and for the first time in Europe since September 2006. "Leatherman", "Yellow Moon", and "Baba O'Riley" (The Who) were on the setlist, but were not played.

"Who You Are" was performed for the first time since September 2011, and for the first time in Europe since November 1996. "Evacuation" was played for the first time since the legendary Philadelphia show in 2009, and for the first time in Europe since June 2000. "All Night" was played for the first time in Europe since August 2009. "Thin Air" was played only for the second time since June 2008, and for the first time in Europe since September 2006. "Sleeping by Myself" was performed full-band for the third time ever.

"Leatherman" was played for the first time since June 13, 2007. "Brother", "Footsteps" and "You Are" also made their 2010 debut. Tom Waits "Jersey Girl" was covered for the first time ever. "Breath", "No Way", "Leaving Here", "Gone", and "Porch" were on the setlist, but were replaced with "Insignificance", "Daughter", and "You Are". concertlist.info: This setlist might be considered as extremely rare: both Undone and Push Me Pull Me were played for only the 5th time ever, and for the first time this year. Sad, Red Mosquito, Bee Girl, Love Reign O'er Me, Rival, Soldier of Love and Crown of Thorns also made their 2010 debut. On the other hand, Do The Evolution missed its first gig this year, after being played for 11 shows in a row. Smile was requested by a female fan on the official internet forum, after she was hospitalized and couldn't make it to the show. At the end of Alive, they paid tribute to the late Ronnie James Dio by playing Black Sabbath's Heaven and Hell riff.

After starting 11 gigs in a row with different songs, Pearl Jam finally used a show-opener for the second time: "Unthought Known". Soundcheck included "Rival", "Breakerfall", "Sad", "Satan's Bed" , "Ain't Talkin' 'Bout Love" (Van Halen), "Love Reign O'er Me" (The Who), "Speed of Sound", "Push Me, Pull Me", and "Last Exit".

concertlist.info: Pearl Jam closed The Spectrum with an incredibly long show, including some big surprises. "Bugs" and "Sweet Lew" were played for the first time ever, as was Devo cover "Whip It". "Out of My Mind" was played for the first time since April 6, 1994, and only for the third time ever. "Pilate" was played for the first time since October 25, 2000, and "I'm Open" for the first time since June 28, 2008. A Bruce Springsteen song and "Soldier of Love" were on the printed setlist, but not played. "Black" wasn't on the printed setlist, but was played anyways. Soundcheck included "Pilate", "Out of My Mind", "Black Red Yellow", "Whip It" and "Sweet Lew".

concertlist.info: It was all about the second encore tonight. The Mama-son trilogy re-appeared on the set for the first time since June 28, 2008, although it was slightly altered with Hunger Strike being played before Alive. Eddie Vedder said "sometimes it takes just one person to make something great", as they were joined on stage by former Temple of the Dog colleague Chris Cornell. They played Hunger Strike together for the first time since October 28, 2003, and the song itself for the first time since September 1, 2006. After that, Alice in Chains guitarist Jerry Cantrell joined the band to close the night with Alive.

Pearl Jam's 2000 European tour ended in tragedy on June 30, with an accident at the Roskilde Festival in Denmark. Nine fans were crushed underfoot and suffocated to death as the crowd rushed to the front. The band stopped playing and tried to calm the crowd when the musicians realized what was happening, but it was already too late. The two remaining dates of the tour were canceled, and the band seriously considered retiring after this event. Pearl Jam was initially blamed for the accident, but was later cleared of responsibility.

One of the performances of Alive was recorded and released as a bonus track for the European release of Ten and also the B-side to many versions of the Jeremy single.
